the file to which to save

This method is called when the data from an entry is to be saved to a file. Typically this method would be called from a gqmv-save-selected-button of a view of Q, although gqm-save-entry is also an API function.

To extend this method, you must reopen the file named by FileName, either before or after the 'call next method.' Alternatively, you could override the format of the logging by writing the data from Entry in your own format, without a 'call next method.'
the queue which is requesting that the entry be saved
the file to which to save the entry

c.PROTOOLS-DOCUMENTATION-DETAILS.ua.PROTOOLS-DESCRIPTION:
The purpose of this subclass is to provide specific methods for gqm-error-entry::gqm-delete and gqm-error-entry::gqm-entry-constructor. There are no class-specific attributes on this class.

Gqm-error-entry is the default entry class for the error-queue.

g2:Structure.g2:sa.DESCRIPTION: The queue on which the entry was posted. Note that if Entry is a gda-alarm-entry, then Queue must be a gda-alarm-queue.

The source of Entry, if applicable. If Entry is a gqm-entry, then any item (e.g. Client)can be passed into this argument; it will not be used. If Entry is a gda-alarm-entry, then source must be a gdl-alarm-source.

You should call gqm-expire-entry from an entry constructor. The procedure waits for the lifetime specified on the gqm-queue attribute, gqm-entry-lifetime, and then removes Entry from all queues upon which it resides. If there is a detail view of the entry at the time the expiration is to take place, it waits for the detail view to be deleted. The Update Latency of the (original) queue is used to determine the polling frequency.

If Entry is a gda-alarm-entry, then gqm-expire-entry additionally logs an expiration event to the history, then removes the entry from all queues (alarm or otherwise).

c.PROTOOLS-DOCUMENTATION-DETAILS.ua.PROTOOLS-DESCRIPTION:
Each queue, optionally, has a logging manager associated with it. The logging manager specifies the file name, the format of the file, and when to change files when creating a permanent log for queue events. This class of logging manager is used for all the built in queues of class gqm-queue. Specifically, the message-queue, error-queue, and explantation queue all use a logging manager of class gqm-logging-manager.

This class extends glf-logging-manager by adding two attributes (see table).

g2:Structure.g2:sa.DESCRIPTION: A symbol to be passed as the Form argument in gqm-time-to-text. This attribute allows you to customize whether the date, the time, or the date and the time is used in the log file when a time stamp is recorded. The class gqm-general-setting allows the details of the format to be specified.

This configurable attribute is not used for logging for instances of this class (see gda-alarm-logging-manager) as comments do not exist at the time entries are logged (on creation). However, this attribute is accessed by the API gqm-save-entry to determine whether or not comments should be written when an entry is saved.

This attribute provides a template used to generate successive file names. In GDA, a different template is used for each built-in queue type. This was done because the actual log file names used are generated based on this attribute and the time. If all four built-in queues were to start logging simultaneously (as happens on startup), they would all write to the same file. For this reason, you should create a new template each time you create a new instance of a gqm-logging-manager.

c.PROTOOLS-DOCUMENTATION-DETAILS.ua.PROTOOLS-DESCRIPTION:
This is the basic class of all entries in the queue system. It is also the class used on the built-in queue instance message-queue.

An entry is created using the call gqm-post-entry on a queue. Gqm-post-entry takes a structure which is passed on to the gqm-entry-constructor method on the entry which is created. Refer to the documentation of gqm-post-entry which gives the attributes on that structure which are defined for the built-in entry classes. This same structure is passed on to the gqm-entry-constructor method.

g2:Structure.g2:sa.DESCRIPTION: This attribute can be accessed directly by an application programmer to add a comment programatically.
The text of the message, as it appears on the tabular display.
A time stamp indicating when the entry was created.

The priority is an integer which is not used by the rest of the queue system. It provides a extra attribute which application programmers may make use of, if they wish. An entry will have a priority which corresponds to the gqm-queue attribute gqm-default-priority of the queue which created it.
The queue to which a new entry is to be posted.
A structure which contains the data to be used in creating the new entry.
A newly created entry of the class named by the gqm-entry-class of Queue
This attribute contains the text of the entry which is to be displayed on the queue view.
When posting to a queue which generated error entries, an error itself can be included in the entry data as an alternative to gqm-text. If this is the case, the attribute gqm-text must be omitted.

For gqm-entry, this is not required. For other entires, this attribute is to contain the source of the of the data. In the case of gda-alarm-entry, the source must be of the class gdl-alarm-source. The source is linked to the entry via the relation the-gqm-source-of

This applies only to gda-alarm-entry. If post entry is called by a GDA object, then the status will be derived from the belief value. A GDA block will use the Output Uncertainty to convert belief values to status. If Logic is discrete, then the belief value must be one of 0.0, 0.5, or 1.0. The status value should be assigned according to the belief value with .TRUE accompanying 1.0, UNKNOWN with 0.5, and .FALSE with 0.0.

This applies only to gda-alarm-entry. This is the fuzzy belief value of the alarm, with value from 0.0 to 1.0. Regardless of whether the logic is discrete or fuzzy, a belief value must be included in the gqm-post-entry call. If the logic is discrete, then pass a value of either 0.0 or 1.0 (or 0.5 if three-way logic is being used, and you wish to specify a belief on unknown).
This applies only to gda-alarm-entry. The attribute contains a collection time (in G2 time, as a float) of the data which caused the alarm.
This applies only to gda-alarm-entry. This is an integer which corresponds to the severity of the alarm

This procedure creates and returns a new entry. The entry is initialized via its gqm-entry-constructor method and then inserted onto to Queue.

The class of the newly-created entry is determined by the gqm-entry-class of Queue. The exception to this is if the gqm-source of the EntryData is a gdl-recurring-alarm. In this is the case, the gda-alarm-queue-attribute, gda-recurring-entry-class, is used to determine the class of the entry.

See also:

    gda-recurring-alarm-entry::gqm-entry-constructor

    gda-alarm-entry::gqm-entry-constructor

    gda-entry-with-uuid::gqm-entry-constructor

    gqm-error-entry::gqm-entry-constructor

    gqm-entry::gqm-entry-constructor


EntryData Structure Description

The required attributes in the EntryData data structure are determined by the class of entry which is ultimately to be created. All entries require a gqm-text (see the gqm-error attribute for a caveat in the case of error entries). All queues except the message queue (which uses entry class gqm-entry) also use the attribute gqm-source. The remaining attributes apply only to gda-alarm-queue.

    <d>   -  day
    <d2>  -  2-digit day
    <df>  -  full day name
    <da>  -  abbreviated day name
    <dor> -  ordinal day
    <m>   -  month
    <m2>  -  2-digit month
    <mf>  -  full month name
    <ma>  -  abbreviated month name
    <apm>  -  A.M. or P.M.
    <h12>  -  hour (12 hour)
    <h24>  -  hour (24 hour)
    <min>  -  minute
    <sec>  -  second

c.PROTOOLS-DOCUMENTATION-DETAILS.ua.PROTOOLS-DESCRIPTION:
The gqm-queue class is the basic class for all the queues within GDA. The error-queue, explanation-queue, and message-queue are all instances of this class.

Attributes of the build-in should not be edited (either manually or programmatically) directly. For manual edits, the configuration panel provides the proper access. For programmatic edits, the appropriate subclass of gdabasic-named-queue-setting should be edited instead. For instances other than the built-in queues, attributes on the queue can be edited directly.

Note that for attributes described for gqm-queue and the queue hierarchy, the effects of changing the attributes (i.e. configuring the queue) are described more thoroughly in the User's Guide material.

This class, and the subclass gda-alarm-queue, can be subclassed and extended. This class can also be specialized by configuring the callback attributes. It is important to realize, also, that queue behavior can be specialized by using other classes. The gqm-queue class should only be subclassed if you are adding attributes or extending the gqm-queue::gqs-clear-queue method. Further, customizations should only placed on the queue (either in the methods or the callbacks), if the custom actions are on the data server side. See the class gqs-view-manager for a way to customize the queue actions using a subscribed view. Finally, if the customizations are associated with additional entry attributes which need to be handled, it might be most appropriate to subclass gqm-entry.

g2:Structure.g2:sa.DESCRIPTION: The symbol gqm-entry or a symbol naming any subclass of gqm-entry. This attribute what class of entry to create when a new entry is posted to the queue using gqm-post-entry

This attribute is not used by GDA's built in queues. The default priority is assigned to the gqm-priority of the gqm-entry created by the queue. This attribute is available for application developer use.
This integer specifies the number of entries which can be maintained in the queue. If additional entries arrive, the oldest will be discarded.
When this attribute is true, receipt of a new entry on the queue will launch a view on all ui-client-items which are connected.
When this attribute is true, showing a new view will be accompanied by a beep.
Whether or not to launch a dialog, prompting the user whether or not to really delete the selected entries.

This attribute is only used by the explanation-queue and the alarm-queue. When a new explanation or alarm entry is created, it will be set to expire in the number of seconds specified in this attribute. If the value of this attribute is 0, then the entries will never expire. See gda-entry-with-uuid for more details.
Typically this attribute will not be used. See gqs-queue for more details.
This attribute should name an instance of a gqm-logging-manager. See gqs-queue
